snippet.textDisplay:
I hear a lot of people talking about public schools not closing down, including mine, but my biology teacher explained to our class a few things

Quick context - I live in a small and poor city, Livingston California, and this might only apply to schools in similar situations to mine -

1. If schools shut down, parents will have to stay home more to take care of their kids. Some of those parents are our very few doctors and nurses, which is something we’re relying heavily on at this exact moment
2. For some students, their only way to have lunch is to go to school. If they’re malnourished, they may become more vulnerable
3. It might sounds somewhat selfish, but all districts will have to make up those days without school. We may lose spring break, we may lose a month of summer break, or we could do online courses with students who could afford it

Our school is taking the most precautions it can, and it’s extremely heartbreaking because that includes all games for athletics and fuel trips to be cancelled. Our seniors who’s sports were in spring are heartbroken, those sports being the last connected to our high school before they went off to start their life.

Mark is absolutely right here. Panic is not what will help us in any crisis. If anything it’s being aware and informed, and doing the best you can to protect yourself and the people around you. This may come off as dumb, but, thought I’d put this on the table :’)

snippet.textDisplay:
Shoutout to my fellow Washington residents who are under quarantine!!

I had it confirmed on Friday the 13th, go figure. I’m a 21 year-old male, and it feels like a glorified flu; only difference being that I got a some canker sores about a day after feeling the other symptoms.

snippet.textDisplay:
God Bless you and your friends and family, Markiplier! If only others were making videos like this, to combat the very dangerous ignorance and spread of misinformation.

If people want some advice on what to do, I have looked up a number of things, and can help. But just know that you are at risk with this virus, even if young and healthy. The CFR for the young, so far, is 0.2% from ages 10 to 40. So, out of every 500 young healthy people, 1 dies. Do you like 1 in 500 odds? Even if you do not die, you can get horrible pneumonia, and your lungs, kidneys, or heart can be scarred. You can also catch this disease more than once, and if you have organ scars, you are much less likely to survive a second time.


If you must go to work, and cannot avoid crowds, I would recommend a mask. Studies of families where 1+ members were infected with the flu virus (much less deadly, but still a virus, so perfectly comparable) show that even a simple surgical mask can greatly decrease your chance of catching the disease. Even a handkerchief or rag wrapped around your face will reduce the number of infected particles which can reach it.

If you can, try to get a respirator with good filters. N100 or P100 filters are the best (ignore the letter, that's just oil-filtration), but N95 is also good. More likely you will end up with a disposable mask of some grade (normally N95), having to make it last as long as you can through the worst times.
